          <div class="section-heading">
            <p class="eyebrow">Impact of root intrusion</p>
            <h2>Common impacts of root intrusion on your sewer</h2>
            <p>Tree roots penetrate sewer lines through small cracks, attracted by the nutrient-rich water inside. Once inside, they cause increasingly serious damage.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="trust-stack">
            <article><span>01</span><div><h3>Clogged sewer lines</h3><p>Roots trap debris and grease, obstructing wastewater flow and causing backups that affect the entire home.</p></div></article>
            <article><span>02</span><div><h3>Cracked or collapsed pipes</h3><p>Expanding roots create fractures or destroy pipe structure entirely, turning a small crack into a major break.</p></div></article>
            <article><span>03</span><div><h3>Sewage backups</h3><p>Blocked pipes force wastewater back into your home through floor drains, toilets, and tubs — a serious health hazard.</p></div></article>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="section section--muted">
        <div class="container split">
          <div>
            <p class="eyebrow">Warning signs</p>
            <h2>Warning signs of root intrusion</h2>
            <p>Watch for these indicators that tree roots may be infiltrating your sewer line.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="callout-list">
            <div><strong>Slow draining water across multiple fixtures</strong><span>Roots are restricting flow in the main sewer line, affecting the entire home.</span></div>
            <div><strong>Frequent clogs in various areas</strong><span>Root masses catch debris and create recurring blockages throughout the system.</span></div>
            <div><strong>Gurgling sounds from drains and toilets</strong><span>Air trapped by root intrusion creates unusual sounds when water flows.</span></div>
            <div><strong>Persistent sewer odors inside or outside</strong><span>Cracked pipes leak sewer gas, creating lingering smells near the home or in the yard.</span></div>
            <div><strong>Abnormally lush grass patches</strong><span>Nutrient-rich water leaking from cracked pipes feeds the lawn above the sewer line.</span></div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

